'''Kawasukune Shrine''' (かわすくねじんじゃ) is a Shinto shrine located in Kawashima, {{ill|lt=Shibukawa City|Q851492|qid=Q851492|1=Shibukawa, Gunma}}, {{ill|lt=Gunma Prefecture|Q129499|qid=Q129499|1=Gunma Prefecture}}. The enshrined deities are {{ill|lt=Hayakitsuhiko-Hayakitsuhime|Q11326733|qid=Q11326733|lt=Hayakitsuhiko no Kami|1=Hayakitsuhiko and Hayakitsuhime}} and {{ill|lt=Hayakitsuhiko-Hayakitsuhime|Q11326733|qid=Q11326733|lt=Hayakitsuhime no Kami|1=Hayakitsuhiko and Hayakitsuhime}}{{Sfn|Shibukawa City History Compilation Committee|1984|p=543}}. It is a {{ill|lt=Shikinaisha|UNKNOWN|lt=minor shrine listed in the Engishiki}} of {{ill|lt=Kōzuke Province|Q1054838|qid=Q1054838|1=Kōzuke Province}}, {{ill|lt=Gunma District|Q5617131|qid=Q5617131|1=Gunma District, Gunma}}. Its former shrine rank was {{ill|lt=Gōsha|Q134917316|qid=Q134917316|1=Gō-sha}}.

=== History ===
It is said to have been founded on September 29, {{ill|lt=Hōki|Q18520676|qid=Q18520676|1=Hōki}} 2 ({{ill|lt=771|Q29950|qid=Q29950|1=771}}){{Sfn|Gunma Prefecture Gunma District Education Association|1925|pp=575-577}}.

According to the shrine records, the Kawasukune Shrine in Hakoshima Village (present-day {{ill|lt=Higashiagatsuma Town|Q1203419|qid=Q1203419|1=Higashiagatsuma, Gunma}} Hakoshima), the Sukune Shrine in Ubajima Village (present-day Ubajima, Shibukawa City; now {{ill|lt=Takeuchi Shrine (Shibukawa City)|Q66085129|qid=Q66085129|lt=Takeuchi Shrine|1=Takeuchi Shrine}}), and the Kawasukune Shrine in Yuage Village (present-day Miyukida, Shibukawa City) were all divided and enshrined from this shrine during the {{ill|lt=Bunan|Q1193586|qid=Q1193586|1=Bun'an}} era ({{ill|lt=1444|Q6420|qid=Q6420|1=1444}}–{{ill|lt=1449|Q6446|qid=Q6446|1=1449}}){{Sfn|Shibukawa City History Compilation Committee|1993|pp=883-884,933-934}}.

Interpreting “Kōha” as “river” and “Sukune” as “straight root,” the shrine name is understood to mean “the main stream of the river.” Because three shrines stood along the {{ill|lt=Agatsuma River|Q1636255|qid=Q1636255|1=Agatsuma River}} in places named Hakoshima, Ubajima, and Kawashima—all containing the word “island”—{{ill|lt=Kizao Ozaki|Q21698487|qid=Q21698487|1=Kisao Ozaki}} explains that the river itself was deified<ref>{{Cite book|ja |title=Research on the Jinmyōchō of Kōzuke Province |date=1974-12-10 |year=1974 |publisher=Ozaki-sensei Book Publication Society |pages=210-212 |last=Ozaki |first=Kizao |author-link=Kizao Ozaki |doi=10.11501/12266236}}{{Registration required}}</ref>.

In July of {{ill|lt=Tenmei|Q1194121|qid=Q1194121|1=Tenmei}} 3 ({{ill|lt=1783|Q7745|qid=Q7745|1=1783}}), the shrine buildings were washed away by mudflows caused by the {{ill|lt=Tenmei Great Eruption|Q106959236|qid=Q106959236|lt=eruption of Mount Asama|1=Tenmei eruption}}, but they were rebuilt at the present location on September 19, Tenmei 5 ({{ill|lt=1785|Q7756|qid=Q7756|1=1785}}){{Sfn|Shibukawa City History Compilation Committee|1993|p=235}}. The main hall dates to the Tenmei era, and the worship hall is believed—based on a {{ill|lt=munafuda|Q8008834|qid=Q8008834|1=Munafuda}}—to have been built in {{ill|lt=Kōka|Q1325317|qid=Q1325317|1=Kōka}} 2 ({{ill|lt=1845|Q7636|qid=Q7636|1=1845}}){{Sfn|Shibukawa City History Compilation Committee|1993|p=236}}.

During the {{ill|lt=Edo period|Q184963|qid=Q184963|1=Edo period}}, a Shugendō temple called Kōmyō-ji existed as the shrine’s {{ill|lt=bettō-ji|Q11396755|qid=Q11396755|1=Bettō-ji}}, but it was abolished after the {{ill|lt=Meiji Restoration|Q8707|qid=Q8707|1=Meiji Restoration}}{{Sfn|Shibukawa City History Compilation Committee|1993|pp=237,960-962}}.

